<font color="#FF0000">READ THE PREVIOUS 50 POSTINGS</font><br>
<tt>Sat Feb 15 17:49:20 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
This is perhaps the most interesting and angry site on the WWW. One month ago I choose to stop posting. Viet Nam was back in my life on a daily basis again, after 30 years and I did not want or like that.  Also the site seemed to have become the Dr.Crazy-Tanker-Big Nurse program, as we threw charges and counter charges at each other.  Since than some of us went on to become e-mail friends.  I was amazed to dial in today and see the count of posts at 119 (almost like seeing the evening news body count in the 1960's?). Sadly, what I have read, going back to mid November and reading every post foward, is nothing has changed, emotionally, just the names of the players.  What does that tell us?<br><br>
I suggest to all the current &quot;posters&quot;, those with PTSD or just normal anger, those with historical facts and those with megathoughts, go back and read the last few months, look for the treads, and the trends, they are there. Alex Hernandez was posting his first, Doc Del was on leave, perhaps taking a break as I was about to do.  By the way, Doc Del, I was the one who did 2 years of bed pans instead of running to Canada-your comment that I lost my credibility was curious-perhaps you might enlighten me as to how that happened or why you think so.<br><br>
A couple of things need to be restated and rested, if indeed we can more on to healing and growth:<br><br>
1. There was no &quot;peace&quot; movement. There was no true &quot;anti-war&quot; movement. There was the Stop the Viet Nam War Movement which was based on one simple fact (which my fellow protestors hated to admit): PROTECT YOUR OWN ASS. (i.e. avoid the draft). That is why the movement disappeared within days of the Fall of Saigon for 90%+ of war resistors.<br><br>
2. A smaller faction within the protest community tried to stop soldiers from going to nam. In Oakland they lay down in front of trains, to make their statement of resistence. This faction truly cared for more than just their own behinds.  Some of them still protest wars, some became tree huggers, others, who knows.   One became the Commander in Chief, but he was into not inhaling along with covering his behind.<br><br>
3. Sure some Viet Vets got spat on, or were treated lousy upon return. That was wrong.  Some &quot;long haired pinko protesors&quot; got beat up and were given &quot;free&quot; haircuts by patriotic redneck god-fearing americans (and veterans), but two injustices do not make for one justice, so to speak. It happened.  Both, the long hair and the soldier in uniform were convinient targets for mostly non thinking fools on both sides. The movie Easy Rider captured this perfectly.<br><br>
4. I used to think, and my first posting on this site, said that I was tired of viet nam vets and their &quot;whinning&quot;. I have learned that I was wrong about that.  This site taught me that rage and pain are alive and well, far more than I thought from the smugness of my office walls.  In WW2 (the big one) returning soldiers had weeks if not months to &quot;decompress&quot; as they were shipped home on ships.  They also were on the winning side of a war that all knew was &quot;just&quot; against the most evil of evils. (except ol Uncle Joe Stalin and his latter mass murders).  The Nam Vet went from jungle to sidewalk in 48 to 72 hours.  No wonder the PTSD barely occured.  No time for decompression led to years of agony, in my opinion, and the need to constantly &quot;set the record straight&quot; of one's involvement. Or to ease the burden of one's sole.  WWII was to save the world from evil. Viet Nam was what? To keep the sampams out of Santa Monica? It was never defined, ill conceived, poorly executed, and a tragedy for all of America, let alone the &quot;natives&quot; caught in the middle.<br><br>
5. Vets of Nam, it is over. Let it go. Acknowledge your anger and your guilt, your victimization and your betrayal. When one serves his country blindly, he is apt to never see the knife coming that stabs him, and that is the case here.<br><br>
6. My prior points, from Honor the Protestor, to why Conscious Objectors (those who had principals and did not run from the draft) never got any acknowledgement or even one G.I.Bill credit is also sad commentary on a country that stupidly threw away so many young lives.   Even today, I wonder why? I suspect that along with who really killed JFK, and other metaphysical questions, I will have to accept the unacceptable, that I will never know the truth (if there is any)...
